# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: StoryBeginnings | Scene: SecondPartOfFuneral
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "Sarah entered the great hall. She scanned the room, looking for her brother."
    new "Sarah entered the great hall. She scanned the room, looking for her brother."

    old "She quickly found Thomas. Her poor brother was trapped in conversation with Marion."
    new "She quickly found Thomas. Her poor brother was trapped in conversation with Marion."

    old "She rushed over to her brother's side."
    new "She rushed over to her brother's side."

    old "Thomas, how are you keeping up?"
    new "Thomas, how are you keeping up?"

    old "Thomas looked at her with gratitude, thanking her with his eyes."
    new "Thomas looked at her with gratitude, thanking her with his eyes."

    old "Ooh, very well, dear Sister, very well indeed. Kind Sir Marion has been keeping me good company by regaling stories about Father's last trip."
    new "Ooh, very well, dear Sister, very well indeed. Kind Sir Marion has been keeping me good company by regaling stories about Father's last trip."

    old "Marion nodded, either not noticing or ignoring the sarcasm."
    new "Marion nodded, either not noticing or ignoring the sarcasm."

    old "I was just telling your brother how your father has left a void that can't ever be filled. But, alas, we must try."
    new "I was just telling your brother how your father has left a void that can't ever be filled. But, alas, we must try."

    old "Marion threw up his hands as if he was in a play, pleading the gods."
    new "Marion threw up his hands as if he was in a play, pleading the gods."

    old "Sarah nodded politely."
    new "Sarah nodded politely."

    old "Honestly, it still feels unreal. There are days where I have to catch myself, remembering that he isn't here anymore."
    new "Honestly, it still feels unreal. There are days where I have to catch myself, remembering that he isn't here anymore."

    old "Take time to deal with the grief."
    new "Take time to deal with the grief."

    old "Sarah was surprised to find Marion seemingly listening for a change."
    new "Sarah was surprised to find Marion seemingly listening for a change."

    old "My own father passed when I was still young."
    new "My own father passed when I was still young."

    old "Marion's perfect visage seemed to crack for a moment. Real emotion."
    new "Marion's perfect visage seemed to crack for a moment. Real emotion."

    old "As the heir to the family, everything fell onto my shoulders. I got so busy, I never really got the time to really sit and deal with the grief. It's always just sort of lingered."
    new "As the heir to the family, everything fell onto my shoulders. I got so busy, I never really got the time to really sit and deal with the grief. It's always just sort of lingered."

    old "You should remember how lucky you are, to have each other."
    new "You should remember how lucky you are, to have each other."

    old "Sarah found herself nodding along to Marion, genuinely this time."
    new "Sarah found herself nodding along to Marion, genuinely this time."

    old "As quickly as the crack in his facade had appeared, she could see him reassert himself."
    new "As quickly as the crack in his facade had appeared, she could see him reassert himself."

    old "Of course, if my family or myself can be of any help to you and your brother in the coming weeks, don't fear to call on us."
    new "Of course, if my family or myself can be of any help to you and your brother in the coming weeks, don't fear to call on us."

    old "Marion, the politican, had returned."
    new "Marion, the politican, had returned."

    old "My family has always been loyal to your father. Consider that loyalty one of many inheritances, passing from him to you both."
    new "My family has always been loyal to your father. Consider that loyalty one of many inheritances, passing from him to you both."

    old "Sarah performed a small bow."
    new "Sarah performed a small bow."

    old "Thank you Marion, that means a lot to us. Both of us."
    new "Thank you Marion, that means a lot to us. Both of us."

    old "She poked her brother in the side, startling him."
    new "She poked her brother in the side, startling him."

    old "Aah, uhm, yes! Thank you for the kind words."
    new "Aah, uhm, yes! Thank you for the kind words."

    old "Thomas performed his own clumsy bow."
    new "Thomas performed his own clumsy bow."

    old "Marion took his cue."
    new "Marion took his cue."

    old "Well, it's late, and I believe that if I keep talking I'll just end up palavering. Take care, my liege, my princess."
    new "Well, it's late, and I believe that if I keep talking I'll just end up palavering. Take care, my liege, my princess."

    old "Marion performed a near perfect bow before leaving."
    new "Marion performed a near perfect bow before leaving."

    old "Sarah wondered if he had overdone it intentionally, mocking her brother's attempt at a bow."
    new "Sarah wondered if he had overdone it intentionally, mocking her brother's attempt at a bow."

    old "But that was the problem with Marion. Even if you knew he was good at hiding his intentions, it didn't make him any easier to read."
    new "But that was the problem with Marion. Even if you knew he was good at hiding his intentions, it didn't make him any easier to read."

    old "The evening carried on, but Marion's departure had signalled to most of the other nobility, that they could leave without facing scrutiny."
    new "The evening carried on, but Marion's departure had signalled to most of the other nobility, that they could leave without facing scrutiny."

    old "One by one, in a seemingly endless procession, the nobles approached Sarah and Thomas, offered their last condolences, and left the castle."
    new "One by one, in a seemingly endless procession, the nobles approached Sarah and Thomas, offered their last condolences, and left the castle."

    old "By now, the great hall had become nearly empty. Some servants still wandered, and the occasional nobleman too drunk to exit gracefully."
    new "By now, the great hall had become nearly empty. Some servants still wandered, and the occasional nobleman too drunk to exit gracefully."

    old "Sarah looked at her brother; dark rings surrounded his eyes."
    new "Sarah looked at her brother; dark rings surrounded his eyes."

    old "Go on, Thomas, you need your rest. There will be a lot more work in the coming days and weeks."
    new "Go on, Thomas, you need your rest. There will be a lot more work in the coming days and weeks."

    old "Thomas did not even protest, he simply turned around and left for his chambers."
    new "Thomas did not even protest, he simply turned around and left for his chambers."

    old "That's when Sarah knew her brother was truly exhausted."
    new "That's when Sarah knew her brother was truly exhausted."

    old "Sarah scanned the great hall. There was nobody left that needed her attention. No more work to be done."
    new "Sarah scanned the great hall. There was nobody left that needed her attention. No more work to be done."

    old "Her eyes fell on her father's casket, now seemingly abandoned near the end of the hall."
    new "Her eyes fell on her father's casket, now seemingly abandoned near the end of the hall."

    old "Tomorrow the priests would render her father's body to the earth, placing him in the family grave, next to Mother."
    new "Tomorrow the priests would render her father's body to the earth, placing him in the family grave, next to Mother."

    old "Reunited at last."
    new "Reunited at last."

    old "Sparing one last glance, Sarah turned around and walked away, knowing this was the last time she would ever see her father."
    new "Sparing one last glance, Sarah turned around and walked away, knowing this was the last time she would ever see her father."

